# {{ .prefix }}-proposing-adr

<!-- awf:section positioning -->
Writes a new ADR to `{{ .vars.adrDir }}/NNNN-kebab-title.md` (status `Proposed`) and commits it. Scope each record to a single load-bearing commitment — one decision per ADR. See `{{ .vars.workflowDoc }}` for the full lifecycle rules and `{{ .prefix }}-adr-lifecycle` for state transitions.
<!-- awf:end -->

## When to invoke

<!-- awf:section when-to-invoke -->
Per `{{ .vars.workflowDoc }}`: load-bearing decisions only — one ADR per decision. Bugfixes and routine refactors do not need an ADR. When in doubt, write the ADR.

Load-bearing triggers include:
{{ range .data.adrTriggers }}- {{ . }}
{{ end }}
<!-- awf:end -->

## Conventions enforced

<!-- awf:section conventions -->
- **Next number:** list `{{ .vars.adrDir }}/NNNN-*.md`, take the highest existing number plus one. Never reuse numbers.
- **Filename:** `NNNN-kebab-title.md`.
- **Template:** copy section structure from `{{ .vars.adrTemplatePath }}` (inline the content via `Write`; do not shell-copy the file).
- **Required frontmatter:** `status` (`Proposed` — initial state), `date` (today, ISO-8601), `supersedes` (array of ADR numbers or `[]`), `superseded_by` (number or `null`), `tags` (≥1 domain label driving `ACTIVE.md` grouping), `related` (array of ADR numbers or `[]`).
- **Required sections:** {{ range .data.adrSections }}{{ . }}, {{ end }}in that order. Delete the authoring checklist before committing.
- **Predecessor flip:** if fully superseding an earlier ADR, update its `status:` frontmatter field to `Superseded by ADR-NNNN` in the same commit.
<!-- awf:end -->

## Procedure

<!-- awf:section procedure-number -->
1. **Pick the next ADR number.** List `{{ .vars.adrDir }}/NNNN-*.md` and take the maximum number plus one.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section procedure-write -->
1. **Write the ADR file** using `Write`. Copy section structure from `{{ .vars.adrTemplatePath }}` and fill all sections:
   - **Context:** the problem, couplings, prior discoveries. Mutable while `Proposed`.
   - **Decision:** numbered items, each a discrete commitment. Numbers matter for partial-item supersedence.
   - **Invariants:** testable textual contracts. Each bullet must be a verifiable property the codebase must maintain.
   - **Consequences:** honest about trade-offs accepted, operational implications, downstream work created or unblocked.
   - **Alternatives Considered:** real options weighed and the one-line reason each was set aside. Skip if there were no genuine alternatives.
   - Delete the authoring checklist before committing.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section state-doc-update -->
1. **Update or create the relevant state doc** under `{{ .vars.stateDocsPath }}` if the ADR materially shifts a domain's current state. Include this file in the same commit as the ADR.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section procedure-predecessor-flip -->
1. **Flip predecessor status** if fully superseding an earlier ADR: update its `status:` frontmatter field to `Superseded by ADR-NNNN` in the same commit.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section readme-index-update -->
1. **Update the README index.** Add a row in the appropriate area table of `{{ .vars.adrReadme }}`. Columns: ADR link, title, Status, Notes.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section invariants-rule -->
1. **Pair each Invariant with a test.** Each Invariants section bullet must be accompanied by at least one `// invariant: <normalised bullet title>` test shipping in the same commit. Run `{{ .vars.adrRegenCmd }}` to confirm.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section procedure-regen -->
1. **Regenerate ACTIVE.md.** Run `{{ .vars.adrRegenCmd }}` to regenerate `{{ .vars.adrDir }}/ACTIVE.md`. Stage the regenerated file. Do not hand-edit `ACTIVE.md`.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section procedure-commit -->
1. **Commit everything in one commit.** Format: `{{ .vars.adrProposeCommitFmt }}`. The commit body names the load-bearing decision and explains why it warrants an ADR. The gate must pass — if the drift test fails, regenerate and re-stage `ACTIVE.md` before retrying.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section autonomous-rule -->
1. **Autonomous continuation.** After the commit, continue to the next chain step without waiting for further approval, per the project's autonomous post-brainstorm rule.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section terminal-step -->
1. **Terminal step: invoke `{{ .prefix }}-reviewing-adr`** via the `Skill` tool, passing the ADR path. The reviewer runs the lens panel and reports findings; route them per the reviewing skill's procedure.
<!-- awf:end -->

## Notes

<!-- awf:section notes -->
- The ADR stays `status: Proposed` through the implementation sequence. It flips to `Accepted` (design final, implementation follows) or directly to `Implemented` (design and implementation land together) in a later commit — that is handled by `{{ .prefix }}-adr-lifecycle`, not this skill.
- `{{ .vars.adrDir }}/ACTIVE.md` is never hand-edited; it is always regenerated via `{{ .vars.adrRegenCmd }}`.
- Decision items are numbered so future ADRs can override a specific item via partial-item supersedence (`related:` frontmatter, predecessor status stays live, successor cites "ADR-NNNN Decision item M" in prose).
- For the full ADR lifecycle, see `{{ .vars.workflowDoc }}`.
<!-- awf:end -->
